what's stopping people from receiving COVID vaccines?¶

an introductory data science tutorial, presented by annie fang¶

With COVID vaccinations rolling out in the US, new reports are broadcasting that vaccinations are plateauing. Naturally, we might think - what's stopping people from receiving COVID vaccines? Is it access? Is it information? Is it low vaccine confidence? And, which populations are most at risk, be it any of the above reasons?

what are we trying to do here?¶

In the following tutorial, we're going to attempt to identify which communities might be most at risk if we consider vaccine hesitancy, a community's vulnerability to disaster, and potential supply-demand challenges.

In addition, we'll take a look at whether there are any correlations between vaccine hesitancy and other variables such as education-level and median household income.

why should this matter to me?¶

Understanding which individuals might be choosing not to or are unable to receive COVID vaccines might lead us towards more targeted marketing, resource-delegation, volunteer efforts, and dissemination of information.

Furthermore, as we move past the highest-risk individuals, based on pre-existing health conditions and occupations, we need a new way to identify risk.

As COVID vaccines roll-out, there are a plethora of reasons as to why individuals might not be getting vaccinated. As such, I hope that this tutorial helps build a bit of empathy and awareness.

data sources¶

In this tutorial, we'll use data collected from two different sources:

1) vaccine hesitancy

The above dataset is provided by the U.S. Department of Health & Human Services and is primarily from derived from the U.S. Census Bureau’s Household Pulse Survey (HPS). You can read more about how the hesitancy rates were estimated on a county-level here%20Concern).

2) education/unemployment data

The above datasets are provided by the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA).

combining and cleaning data¶

Now that we've found some appropriate data, we're going to take a stab at combining these separate data sources.

For that, the first thing we'll need to do is access our data - let's do this using the Python package pandas.

pandas will let us play around with our datasets, which are in the form of .xls and .csv files, and turn them into matrix-like objects called dataframes. The pandas package is full of functionality that allows us to perform tasks such as removing columns/rows, filtering for data that meets specific conditions, grouping data by feature, handling missing data, and much more. You can read more about pandas here.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd

# load in all 3 datasets into pandas dataframes
hesitancy = pd.read_csv("vaccine_hesitancy.csv")

# the sheet_name parameter lets us read in a single sheet, since .xls documents often contain multiple Excel sheets
education = pd.read_excel("education.xls", sheet_name="Education 1970 to 2019")
unemployment = pd.read_excel("unemployment.xls", sheet_name="Unemployment Med HH Income")

Since this data wasn't necessarily intended to be used in the form of a pandas dataframe, we'll likely need to do some tinkering to get things into a cleaner format.

That being said, let's take a look at one of our datasets:

# merge the vaccine hesitancy and education datasets together using the FIPS codes, which are unique to each county in the US

combined_df = pd.merge(combined_df, unemployment, left_on='FIPS Code', right_on='fips_txt')

combined_df = combined_df.drop(columns=[ 'State_y', 'Area name', 'fips_txt', 'Stabr', 'area_name'])

exploratory data analysis¶

Yay! We've finally gotten all of our data into a more workable format - it's time to (figuratively) bash some rocks against each other and see what shows up.

To do so, we're going to visualize some of our data and see if any promising trends appear. seaborn and matplotlib are two packages that will help us visualize our data. You can explore these packages here and here, respectively.

As example, we've plotted a couple of variables against hesitancy to see what happens. Here, we slapped on a linear regression line to better visualize if there might be some sort of linear trend in any of these relationships (however, this does not mean a linear regression model is appropriate for predicting vaccine hesitancy).

And, just for fun, we visualized the distribution of vaccine hesitancy by state, which tells us that some states have huge variations in vaccine hesitancy, such as New Mexico (NM) and Virginia (VA). Plus, some states like South Dakota (SD) and Idaho (ID) have what appears to be binomial distributions.

Going back to the scatterplots, as you might be able to see, some of these variables don't seem to indicate a strong linear relationship with vaccine hesitancy, specifically SVI, unemployment rate, and percent of adults with less than a high school diploma. On the other hand, median household income and the percentage of adults look promising. However, since these two variables are likely to be strongly correlated to each other (higher paying jobs typically correlate with higher degrees of education), a multi-regression doesn't seem appropriate. If you're curious about multi-regression models and its assumptions, you can check out this resource.

So instead, let's just take a look at how well a linear regression model fits using median household income to predict vaccine hesitancy.

machine learning¶

But FIRST, is it meaningful to use a linear regression model with these variables?

In order to generate meaningful results using a linear regression model, we have to satisfy 4 assumptions (more here):

  1. There exists a linear relationship
  2. The residuals are independent (ie. residuals don't correlate with time)
  3. The residuals are homoscedastic (aka. we have constant variance of our model's residuals for all values of median household income)
  4. The residuals are normally distributed

Now, going through each assumption: we suspect that (1) holds true based on the previous visualizations we generated earlier. (2) doesn't really have to do with us since we're not dealing with time-series data.

So, let's investigate (3) and (4).

generating a linear regression model¶

The statsmodels package (as you might have gathered from the name) provides tools for statistical analysis, including estimating various statistical models, of which linear regression is one. If you're interested in what else statsmodels has to offer, check out the official documentation here.

In [71]:
import statsmodels.api as sm

# use statsmodel to fit the data to a linear regression model
combined_df['median_household_income_tenthousands'] = combined_df['Median_Household_Income_2019'] / 10000
X2 = sm.add_constant(combined_df['median_household_income_tenthousands'])
est = sm.OLS(combined_df['Estimated hesitant'], X2)
model = est.fit()

print(f'vaccine hesitancy = {model.params.median_household_income_tenthousands:.4f} * median household income + {model.params.const:.4f}')

vaccine hesitancy = -0.0142 * median household income + 0.2749

As you can see, our model presents that for every 10k increase in median household income, a county is predicted to have roughly ~1.4% less vaccine hesitancy in that same county. This might not seem like a lot, but 1% of a county can mean huge numbers in context. For example, Prince Georges County has nearly 1 million people - so 1% is ten thousand people!

However, keep in mind that we haven't established how strong the predictive power of this model is, and we have yet to fulfill our 4 assumptions.

In [83]:
print("p-values:")
print(model.pvalues)

print("r-squared:")
print(model.rsquared)

p-values:
const                                    0.000000e+00
median_household_income_tenthousands    1.293974e-127
dtype: float64
r-squared:
0.18503892645879838

So, what do these numbers mean? Well, the significance/p-values of our models' variables are very close to 0, we would theoretically reject the supposed null hypothesis that no relationship exists between median household income and vaccine hesitancy.

However, this doesn't mean that the model we have is a good one (and we STILL haven't proven that this data is worthy of a mighty linear regression model). Low and behold, our r^2 value is quite low - this means only ~18.5% of vaccine hesitancy can be explained by median household income.

residuals and assumptions 3 + 4¶

Now, to finally figure out whether all the work we've done was all for naught or not (pun-intended).

We'll start by calculating the residuals:

In [74]:
# calculate the residuals
combined_df['expected_vaccinehesitancy'] = model.params.median_household_income_tenthousands*combined_df['median_household_income_tenthousands'] + model.params.const
combined_df['residual'] = combined_df['Estimated hesitant'] - combined_df['expected_vaccinehesitancy']

And then checking for constant variance (3),

In [88]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
sns.scatterplot(x = "median_household_income_tenthousands", y = "residual", data = combined_df)
plt.show()

And while we're at it, checking for normality (4)

In [82]:
plt.figure(figsize=(4, 8))
sns.violinplot(y = "residual", data = combined_df)
plt.show()

At this point, we see that we don't have a normal distribution of residuals, neither do we seem to have constant variance. So, it seems the assumptions for a linear regression model were NOT met.

However, not everything is for naught - you might notice that there almost a binomial distribution of residuals, which might indicate other variables at play that might be confounding the use of median household income as a predictor.

In fact, if we think about it more closely, what does median household income even represent? What happens to the meaning of median household income if an individual is living in New York City vs rural Georgia? Then, should we be normalizing our data respective of cost of living?

Aha! Luckily, in our vaccine hesitancy dataset, there's a variable for median household income as a percentage relative to the state's median household income.

Let's see what happens if we take a look at this variable with respect to hesitancy.

In [100]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
sns.regplot(data=combined_df, x="Med_HH_Income_Percent_of_State_Total_2019", y="Estimated hesitant")
plt.show()

Now, we don't see much of a linear relationship at all, so it's time to go back to the drawing board.

conclusion¶

While we didn't identify a new variable to associate with higher vaccine hesistancy, we can observe which states seem to have the highest median vaccine hesitancies.

Through this tutorial, we hope that the difficulty of creating meaningful data analysis is apparent, and that problems involving human psychology, such as whether or not someone plans to get vaccinated, is multi-faceted and complex.

In fact, here's the twist of the entire vaccine hesitancy dataset (and a wake-up call to the potential dangers of the connotation of "vaccine hesitancy" and media reporting): the HPS survey also asked individuals why they are not planning on receiving a COVID vaccine or haven't received a COVID vaccine yet, which can be accessed on the HPS Census Data site. For any week's worth of data, Table 6 under Health Tables provides this data (however, in a very non-pandas digestible form). Just from this data alone, we can see that there are plethora of reasons contributing to the single number representing vaccine hesitancy.

more resources¶

Like most problems involving humans, it's complicated.

If you want to learn more about what might be influencing COVID vaccine roll-out, you can checkout the following resources:

  • Surgo Ventures' U.S. COVID-19 Vaccine Coverage Index

    Surgo Ventures has quantified a multitude of factors that might increase the difficulty of attaining full community vaccination coverage, including historic undervaccination, sociodemographic barriers, healthcare infrastructure constraints, healthcare accessibility barriers, and irregular care-seeking behavior.

  • HPS Census Data

    The Household Pulse Survey (HPS) has been and is currently collecting data regarding the impacts of COVID on people's live as part of the U.S. Census Bureau. Here, you can see the exact week's of raw data that was used by the CDC and U.S. Department of Health & Human Services to compute the vaccine hesitancy data that was used in this tutorial.
